{"/service/ndnp/hihouml/batch_hihouml_gonzalo_ver01/data/sn85047084/00294557568/1907100401/0348.xml":{"full_text":"9m frtf\nTJ. S. WEATHER EUHEAU, October 3. Last 2i tours' rainfall, .00.\nTemperature, Max. 83; Min. 71. Weather, fair.\nSUGAE.-96 Degree Test Centrifugals. 3.95c.; per Ton, J7S.00.\n88 Analysis Beets, 9s. 7UL; per Ton, $80420.\nHONOLULU, HAWAII TERRITORY, FRIDAY; OCTOBER 4, 1907.\nVOL. XLVI., NO 7849-'\nPRICE FIVE CENTS.\nOPPORTUN\nFOR W\nN\n1\nITY\nIL-TO-DO\nAMERICANS\nFarmers With Some Capital Recommended by\nSecretary Straus to Come to the\nHawaiian Islands.\nCOLLECTOR CHAMBERLAIN\nRESIGNS HIS POSITION\n(Special Cablegram to Advertiser.)\nWASHINGTON, October 3. Roy H. Ctamberlain, Collector of Internal\nRevenue at Honolulu, has resigned on account of the illne of his wife.\nEBNEST G. WALKER.\ns\nI .think, would find it to their ft\nI\n;.V 1 \"Well-to-do American laborers,\nadvantage to go there (the Hawaiian Islands), as the territorial gov-\nC' jj ernment is desirous 'of giving them every facility to establish them-\nfc\nselves, especially those who follow agricultural pursuits.\" Oscar S.\nJ Straus, Secretary of Commerce and Labor.\nIn the Chicago Post, of September 3, Secretary Straus gives his impres\nsions of Hawaii, expressing the idea that American agriculturists would prosper\nby coming to these islands. The interview is as follows:\nRoosevelt or Taft is the demand of 1 and he has addressed himself to the\nhs\"PannhH'nnnAr'i)ia at urtt and I work with energy.\ni\nTJorthwest, according to Oscar S.\nStraus, Secretary of \"Commerce and\nLabor, who arrived in Chicago today\nfrom the Hawaiian Islands, and who\nlias been pursuing his course 'leisurely\ntoward the East.\nBeyond that one statement,' however,\nthe1 secretary would not talk much of\npolitics.\n\"The sentiment that I have found in\nvery section of the .country I have\nvisited is an enthusiastic wish and de\ntermined desire for Roosevelt,\" said\nMr. Straus, \"and everybody knows of\nthe position the President had taken,\nthey all seemed to hope that condi\ntions would compel him to accept the\nnomination. The only other name that\nI heard in -connection with the presi\ndency was Taf t.n\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK .IS BRIGHT.\nRegarding his trip generally the sec\ncretary was -willing to talk more freely,\nand was enthusiastic over the condi\ntions commercial and agricultural.\n\"The mission of my trip,, he said,\n\"was to acquaint myself with the field\nwork of the Department of Commerce\nand Dabor, and to come into personal\ntouch with tha men who are perform\ning this .work. I left Washington on\nJune 20 and from there went to Mon\ntreal and along the Canadian border\nto Vancouver inspecting en route the\noffices at Montreal, \"Winnipeg, Van\ncouver and the intermediate staffs of\nthe Immigrant and steamboat inspec\ntion service.\nHawaiian Islands, spending ten days\nin Honolulu and vicinity, and found\nconditions there encouraging and pros\nperous. The chief Industry is sugar,\nto which recently has been added the\ncultivation of pineapples. The finest\npineapples in the world are grown\nthere; They- also \"have begun rubber\ncultivation, and the indications are\nthat It will be an important Industry.\nAMERICAN SPIRIT IN ISLES.\n\"The American spirit dominates, and\nthe white people treat the natives With\ngreat sympathy. A larger white pop\nulation i3 greatly desired in order to\nkeep the equilibrium. The islands need\ncloser connection .with the mainland,\nand the merchants there T repeatedly\nhave presented their wishes that the\nnavigation laws might be amended\ntemporarily until more frequent com\nmunication by American bottoms can\nbe established profitably.\n'\"I believe if thepeople of this cottrt\ntry were more familiar with the at\ntractions of Hawaii large numbers of\ntourists would go there and spend some\nmonths during the winter as well as\ndurin'g the summer. The climate the\nwhole year round Is as attractive as\nthat of Egypt during the winter\nmonths, and is far superior to the\nRiviera,, and more beautiful than Bar\nHarbor. v.:\nGOOD CHANCE FOR WORKERS.\n\"Well-to-do f American laborers, I\nthink, would find it to their advantage\nto go there, as the territorial govern\nment Is desirous of giving them every\nfacility to establish themselves, espe-\n3 f :fi\na 1 1 i\n2\njMtiirtfimMiiiii\" rnr'n liriiiiiiiiTitii\"- -\"r-'-r iirinni vniirniinTTfiri r Tri '-f -f-i\"Tf riir f\" ----'-f-i'--:\nOPENE'\nUPPLIES\nLEET\nFO\n0\nTHE F\nSix Million Pounds for Maintenance of the Men\nof the Pacific Squadron Coast\nPolitics Grow Warm.\n(Associated Press Cablegrams.!\nWASHINGTON, October 4 Bids were opened by the Navy\nauthorities here yesterday for the supplying of six million pounds\nof supplies for the fleet which is to sail shortly for the Pacific.\nWILL BE IN PACIFIC REGULARLY.\nCAIRO, Term., October 3. In an address here President Roose\nvelt spoke of the trip of the battleship fleet to the Pacific He said\nthat in his opinion, the fleet should be kept alternately on the At\nlantic and Pacific V\n3 MANY REPUBLICANS WILL\nBOLT THE PARTY TICKET\nSAN FRANCISCO, October 4. The minority among the dele\ngates present at the Republican convention, at which Daniel A.\nRyan received the nomination for mayor, have notified the party\nleaders that they propose supporting Mayor Taylor for reelection\nin opposition to the party nominee.\n3\nROY H. CHAMBEELAIN, WHO HAS RESIGNED THE COLLECT\nTOESIUP OF INTERNAL REVENUE FOB HAWAII.\nMr. Chamberlain was nominated by\nthe late President MoKinley on De-\ncember 6, 1900, and confirmed as col\nlector by the Senate without delay. He\nis a son-in-law of Congressman Hcd-\nburn of Iowa, who has all along been\na great and good friend, of .Hawaii,\nfrom visits here being well-known to\nmany residents.\n'With his wife and two children Mr.\nChamberlain arrived here in the steam\n(Contlnued on Page Four.)\na a c r, cially those who follow agricultural\nsound to Taooma and Seattle, and! -r j\nthence to Portland and San Francisco.\nAt each of these places I found the\nconditions of the immigrant service,\nthe lighthouse service, the commercial\naffairs generally to be satisfactory.\nThe only complaint I heard was of the\nlack of labor.\nFAITH IN INFORMATION BUREAU\n\"I am in hopes that the new bureau,\nthe bureau of Information, which' was\ncreated by the last Congress, will be\nof great service In advising and direct\ning tabor immigrants to the section of\ncountry, where their services are In\npursuits, I believe a new hand-weav'\ning carpet industry could be establish\ned there with profit and great success,\nas the native Ha waiians have a great\neye for color, which they have 'at\ntained in their basket-weaving indus-\ntry.\" vi'-;.\nMr. Straus is accompanied by Mrs.\nStratus, his son Roger and his private\nsecretary, T. L. Weed. The party is\nen route to Oyster Bay. where Mr.\nStraus will go to lay before President\nRoosevelt the results of his trip. The\nvisitor stopped at the Auditorium An\nnex, and will leave this evening for the\nMOID\ngreat demand. At the head of this new East. iTurig the day the, secretary\nbureau I placed Terrence V. Powderly, called on 1 'Stmaster Campbell.\nASIATIC IMMIGRATION N\nMUST BE RESTRICTED\nUnder the heading. \"Hindoos No the black belt of the South; the situa\ntion of two mutually unassimilabls\nraces occupying the same territory and\ncompeting with each other Industrially\nand socially..\nWhites will not mix with Japanese\nor Hindoos. That, aside from all the\nory, is a definite fact which can not\nbe changed. We must, therefore, take\nLess Menacing than Japanese Immi\ngrants,\" the San Francisco Bulletin\nsays editorially:\nThe riots against the Hindoo laborers\nat Bellingham are the first symptom\nof a new racial problem that will af\nfect, within a short while, the entire\nPacific Coast.\nHindoos are flocking to this country\nIn large numbers. They are accustom\ned to live at the point of starvation,\nand as laborers they will underbid not\nonly the whites, but the Japanese as\nwell. They are British subjects, more\nover, and have the treaty rights of\nEnglishmen.\nWathin a year or two the United\nStates will be compelled by circum\nstances to adopt a definite and de\ncisive policy toward Asiatic immigra\ntion and stick to It. It is Inevitable\nthat the policy of this government, no\nI matter whether it may displease other\n1 powers, shall be one of exclusion. Stu\nk dents, tourists and other non-compet-\nitors in the labor market may be ad-\nAmitted, but laborers must be kept out.\nV i This nolirv will h fnroprt\nthe instinct of self-preservation. The\nopposition to the Asiatic u laborer\nsprings not from mere racial bigotry,\nbut from a clear perception that unre\nstricted immigration of that kind will\nlead to intolerable social and Industrial\nevils. Te exclude Japanese and Hin\ndoos may seem a harsh measure, but\nIt is better to adopt that measure, no\nmatter what it leads to, than to per\nmit the development on the Pacific\nCoast of a situation similar to that In\nN TO STS\nLOUIE'S SUIT\nDefendants Allege It Is Male\nFides and a Fishing\nExcursion.\nSome important papers were filed yes\nterday in the $400,000 damage suit of\nW. J. Lowrie against II. P. Baldwin\nand the Castles. They were filed in\nconnection with the motion of the\nplaintiff for an order for the defend\nants to produce certain papers, a mo\ntion which came up before Judge Kob-\nlhson yesterday morning.\nThis motion asked for an order re\nquiring the defendants to' produce what\nthe plaintiff described as the syndi\ncate agreement for the purchase of\nthe Hawaiian Commercial Sugar Co.\nstock,\" and the contract between Low\nrie and the Castle Estate. It will be\nremembered that Lowrie in his com\nEASE A LITTLE\npmiE\nMunicipal political affairs in San Francisco appear to be in a bad muddle.\nPrior to the Kepublican convention, which was held on September 24, it was\nsupposed that Mayor Taylor would receive the endorsement and appear upon\nthe tickets of all three political parties in the city, the Republican, Democratic\nand Laborites. At the Eepublican convention he received the votes of forty\nfive delegates out of a total of one hundred and forty-nine. These forty -five\nconstitute\" the minority which have bolted the ticket. Following-theTnomlnation\nof Ryan, the Labor party -placed in nomination P. II. McCarthy, known\namong his opponents as \"Blatherskite McCarthy,\" and the only regular\nticket upon which Mayor Taylor's name will appear as a candidate is that\nof the Democrats. This nomination he received on. October 1.\nMEXICO'S GREAT HONOR TO\nTHE SECRETARY OF STATE\nCabin Passengers May Land in\nLess Than Seven Day\nPeriod.\nCITY OF MEXICO, October 4. Secretary Root is here as the\nguest of the Chamber of Deputies, which has been convened espe\ncially to greet him. This action on the part of the Mexican Gov\nernment is the greatest honor this republic has ever shown to any\nforeign guest\nDETROIT WINS AMERICAN LEAGUE.\nSecretary Root is paying an official visit to Mexico with a main purpose\nof consulting with President Diaz, on behalf of President Roosevelt, regarding\nthe proposed peaee conference to be held in Washington among the delegate\nof all the Central American republics. It is the special desire of both the\nThere need be no more seven-day President of Meiico and the American President to bring, about a settled state\nsteamer trips between this city and j of affairs politically in Central America.\nSan Francisco, according to a decision\nmade by Dr. Carl Ramus of the Marine\nHospital Service, as the result of a\ncable message received by him yester\nday from Acting Surgeon General A.\nH. Glennan. The text of the cable re\nceived was as follows:\n\"Washington, D. C.\n\"Dr. Carl Ramus.\n\"You are authorized, if In your opin\nion safe, to permit the landing of cabin\npassengers on vessels disinfected In\nSan Francisco before the limit of seven\ndays.\n\"A. H. GLENNAN,\n\"Acting Surgeon General.\"\nWhen asked what view he would\nCHICAGO, October 4.The championship of the American\nBaseball League has been won by the Detroit Club.\nIn the files received yesterday the standing of the Detroit players was\n.600, having won eighty-four games and lost fifty-six. At that time, September\n25, the Detroita were tied with the Philadelphias, Chicago being a close third,\nonly eight points behind. The race for the American League pennant has this\nseason been very close and the outcome was only settled by the game yester\nday at Chicago.\none race is superior or inferior to the\nother. It means, simply, that the races\nare different from each other.\nThe an ti-Japanese outbreak in Van\ncouver, a city belonging to a power\nwhich is the ally and closest friend of\nJapan, demonstrates that the feeling\nSECRETARY TAFT HAS SAILED.\n-KOBE, October 4. Secretary Taft sailed last night for Manila.\npiaint alleges hat this contract, for take of the matter, since it had been\nIt Into account. It does not mean that I breach of which he sues for damages, left to his discretion, Dr. Ramus said\nmt raiA So iiroilrfci n in f Grim ti tho i I\ngrew out or tne acquirement, contract-1 that he would certainly allow the cabin\ned for but not actually acquired at thef passengers from the vessels Jto land,\ntime, of a control of the Hawaiian j but that in the matter of steerage pas\nCommercial Sugar Co. sengers it was a different matter. The yesterday he was entertained by General Kuroki.\nI cable messac-A had not eriven anv in- I J\nio tnis motion Castle Withinsrton\ni aiiutuuiiN in r rti 11c wuuiu\nagainst the Japanese, is not affected representing- all the defendants except not think it a wise plan to allow them\nby boundary lines or nationality, but j H.- P. Baldwin, and Kinney and Marx I to land in less than the required pe\noriginates In racial and industrial con- representing Baldwin, filed objections,\nvxi vwjcl KH. tlJC\n